Queen Elizabeth II is the most popular Royal Family member according to British public opinion polling, and with more than 70 years of royal service under her belt, it’s not hard to see why. The Queen ascended the throne in 1952, and since then has remained dedicated to her royal duties, even at the age of 96. Read on for 70 facts about the life, family and reign of Queen Elizabeth II. Queen Elizabeth II was born HRH Princess Elizabeth of York on April 21, 1926. Elizabeth was born at 17 Bruton Street in Mayfair, her maternal grandfather’s house in the capital. The Princess had one sister, Princess Margaret, who died in 2002. At the time of her birth, Princess Elizabeth was third in line to the throne behind her father Prince Albert (future King George VI) and uncle Prince Edward (future King Edward VIII). Princess Elizabeth became heir presumptive to the throne in 1936 at the age of 10. She fluently speaks two languages, English and French. The future Queen lived through World War 2 between 1939 and 1945. Elizabeth met her future husband Prince Philip at the Royal Naval College in Dartmouth in 1939 when she was 13 years old. Elizabeth’s first foreign tour was in 1947 when she accompanied her parents to southern Africa. Elizabeth and Philip's engagement was announced on July 9, 1947, when the future Queen was aged 21. Her engagement ring includes 11 diamonds from the collection of Philip’s mother Princess Alice. The happy couple married at Westminster Abbey on November 20, 1947. The Queen wore the Queen Mary Fringe Tiara, which has 47 diamond bars separated by smaller diamond spikes. Elizabeth’s wedding dress was designed by Norman Hartnell and was embellished with 10,000 seed pearls. The Government allowed the future Queen an extra 200 ration coupons for her stunning gown. Elizabeth and Philip received 2,500 wedding gifts from around the globe upon their marriage. Their first child Prince Charles was born on November 14, 1948. Prince Charles was born just six days shy of his parent’s first wedding anniversary. Elizabeth’s only daughter Princess Anne was born on August 15, 1950. Princess Elizabeth succeeded the throne on February 6, 1952, after the death of her father.  Queen Elizabeth II became the nation’s 40th monarch since William the Conqueror. The Queen was 25 years old when she took the throne. Queen Mary became the first Queen to see her grandchild ascend the throne. The Queen was 27 when she was crowned in June 1953. The Queen was the 39th sovereign to be crowned at Westminster Abbey. She was the sixth Queen to have been crowned in Westminster Abbey in her own right, with the first being Queen Mary I in 1553. The Queen wore the George VI State Diadem on the way to the coronation, which holds 1,333 diamonds and 169 pearls. A total of 8,251 guests attended the Queen's coronation ceremony at Westminster Abbey. St Edward's Crown, which the Queen wore during her coronation service, weighed four pounds and 12 ounces. The Cullinan I diamond, or the Great Star of Africa, in the Queen’s sceptre weighs 530.2 carats. Some 27 million people in the UK watched the coronation ceremony on TV. The Queen’s coronation was the first in Britain to be televised to the masses. Another 11 million people tuned in to hear the coronation on the radio. The Queen is the second Elizabeth to reign in England, with the first being Queen Elizabeth I from 1558 to 1603. The Queen made her first Christmas broadcast from overseas in 1953 from New Zealand. The Queen celebrated her Silver Jubilee in 1977. In her Silver Jubilee year, the Queen toured 36 counties in the UK. The Queen’s Golden Jubilee fell in 2002. By the time of her Golden Jubilee, the Queen had owned more than 30 corgis. Three British monarchs have publicly celebrated their Golden Jubilee, including King George III, Queen Victoria and Queen Elizabeth II. The Queen’s Diamond Jubilee took place in 2012. Only two British monarchs have ever celebrated their Diamond Jubilee, Queen Elizabeth II and Queen Victoria. The Queen was the first British monarch to reach a Platinum Jubilee. On September 9, 2015, the Queen surpassed Queen Victoria’s record to become Britain’s longest-reigning monarch ever. Few monarchs have reigned for longer than the Queen, with the longest-reigning monarch of a sovereign state being King Louis XIV of France (72 years, 110 days). Sobhuza II was the longest-reigning monarch of all time, reigning over Swaziland for 82 years and 254 days. The Queen’s son Prince Charles is the longest-serving heir apparent in British royal history. At the age of 96, the Queen is the oldest British monarch ever. Five different portraits of the Queen have been used on UK coinage during her reign. The Queen spends most of her time at four residences: Buckingham Palace, Windsor Castle, Balmoral and Sandringham. The Queen’s Crown Windsor Estate spans some 15,800 acres. The Queen has four children, Prince Charles, Princess Anne, Prince Andrew and Prince Edward. The Queen has eight grandchildren: Peter Phillips, Zara Tindall, Prince William, Prince Harry, Princess Beatrice, Princess Eugenie, Lady Louise Windsor and James, Viscount Severn. The Queen became a grandmother in 1977 upon the birth of Peter Phillips, when she was 51. The Queen has 12 great-grandchildren to date. The Queen became a great-grandmother in 2010 when Peter Phillips’s daughter Savannah was born in 2010 when the Queen was 84. The Queen was married to Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh for 73 years. The Queen and Prince Philip celebrated their Platinum Wedding Anniversary in 2017. The Queen’s beloved mother, Queen Elizabeth, The Queen Mother, was the longest-living British Royal Family member when she died in 2002, aged 101 years and 238 days. The Queen Mother's record was surpassed by her sister-in-law Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester, who died in 2004 aged 102 and 309 days. As of 2002, the Queen had 30 godchildren. The Queen has two birthdays - her real one is April 21, and her public official birthday is held on a Saturday in June every year with Trooping the Colour. During the Queen's reign, there have been 14 prime ministers, with the first being Winston Churchill. Tony Blair was the first prime minister born during the Queen’s reign in 1953. The Queen is head of state in 15 countries, including the UK. Globally, 54 independent countries make up The Commonwealth, which the Queen heads. Some 2.5 billion people live in Commonwealth countries around the world. According to the Commonwealth website, 32 of the world's 42 small states are Commonwealth members. The amount of the Sovereign Grant for the financial year 2022-23 is £86.3million. The Queen has attended 39 Royal Variety shows since 1945. As of 2013, more than 1,600 races have been won by horses owned by the Queen. The Queen’s Platinum Jubilee celebrations will be held over four days on June 2 to June 5.